NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Yvon's 5D bid is quite reasonable. Remember, if they have a fit, you have a fit, and on this hand it is likely to be in diamonds from Yvon's perspective. It turns out 5D is down 1, but if the spade finesse works 5D makes. |
PG| ***** 82 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, let's talk about if Linda should bid 6C. It could be right. However, there are a couple of factors which argue against a 6C bid. She  has no singletons or voids and she has points in our suits. So, her hand is not bad on defense. Therefore, I think she should hope that she pushed us to a non-making game. There is a saying "the 5 level belongs to the opponents." That is definitely an oversimplification, but it has some truth. What it means is, that it is ok to bid 5 over 4 but it is not as likely to be right to bid 5 over 5. |
PG| ***** 83 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|And on this hand, that turns out to be true as they can't make 5C and we can't make 5D. In summary, I think Yvon's 5D bid was correct but I think Linda should hope she has some defense and pass 5D. There are certainly plenty of layouts, given the same cards in both hands, but different distributions, where 5D makes. Again, preempts make things tough, for both sides. It is more a matter of guessing and using sound principles.|
